text: Thank you, Ashley. The first two strategies I worked on were asset allocation strategies, targeted funds, manager payout funds, which has a lot to do with saving for retirement and how to spend down in retirement. And I think it's very relevant because there are really two points. One is that currently the retirement 401k space in some way is highly regulated. So for example, the infrastructure is not there. There are very few firms which offers some of the more innovative approaches like ETFs. I think like probably 90% of retirement plans don't allow a person to invest in low cost ETF, low cost active ETF. And ETF, as both of us agree, has been really an innovation in the last 20 years, not just in tax. I mean, tax advantage is a big part of ETF, but ETF, the trading of ETFs, the trading of ETFs, the trading of ETFs, the trading of ETFs, is you can trade during the day. If you were to have an ETF, it's much more portable. If you have a mutual fund, the trading costs on TD or the other companies is close to $40 for a retail investor. But a lot of ETFs is really commission free. Of course, we don't want to encourage people saving for retirement to trade unnecessarily in timing. But what I'm seeing is that some of the innovations in financial markets, because the way the retirement landscape right now, in the U.S., is very different from the way it is in the U.S. wasn't able to get into targeted funds. I think this area where things get a little bit moved toward more innovations and the government loosened up some of the restrictions, it would have helped get innovation more into retirement. The second thing is really asset allocation, because in asset management, and you and I both know, it's very dominated by a few companies. In the place where the entry cost, entry barrier is high, then some of the innovation wasn't able to get in. So for example, I personally believe in tactical asset allocation. I believe it just like factor timing, it's tactical asset allocation is very, very hard. But in some extreme situations, when valuation gets too high, for example, there are benefits of tactical asset allocation. And Professor Siegel, who recently have written a paper about tactical asset allocation, he said that it's very hard to get in. And he said that it's too expensive to get in. So I think there's some kind of tactical allocation across sectors as well. And it's purely based on value. When a sector gets too expensive, you will think there's something which over a long run that some kind of tactical allocation would help. So I personally agree that some element of tactical allocation should be in a glide path. But of course, you're competing against very big companies. So it's going to take a lot of education from you, from everyone to get people. An ordinary person really have to spend their time and resources to investigate if there's tactical allocation, just like active funds. So I think that's another area, I will say second innovation. So the first is more kind of financial instruments. That's innovation like ETFs and a little bit of technical asset allocation. The third area, which Wisdentree actually happened to have a lot of expertise in this is that we have a senior advisor, Professor Coughlin from MIT's AgeLab. The way he thought about retirement is not most of the glide path assumes. Most of the glide path just assumes there's one monolithic retirement. You retire, then that's it. It's almost like you're working, then that's it. Without realizing that we could have a young, no kids, young with kids, career, career age. Retirement it's the same. Particularly when a person is retired. A person has 20, 30 years of retirement horizon. So Professor Coughlin mentioned that if you are healthy in that first stage of your retirement, you actually need a lot of income because you want to go around the world and visit China or Spain. So all these requires you to have income without having to sell down your assets. Yet because your retirement horizon is still high, you may not want to dial down your equity allocations that fast. So all these, I do believe that the other innovations that will gradually get into the asset allocation glide path. And 10 or 20 years ago, a person's access to a glide path is simple just through one targeted funds. And that's pretty much the only choice you have unless you have an expert doing it for you. But going forward, there are a proliferation of model portfolios. And that really will significantly change your life. It's going to change the way you could manage your money because it's very costly to set up a fund, particularly a public traded fund. There's as easy as so much regulations. But if you have a model portfolio that you could sign yourself up on it, you won't be committed to a particular fund. So that is another area I see more innovations will come for glide path. It also provides a competitive landscape. So that smaller shops. So who have knowledge and expertise in this area could have a shot, not at the model portfolio level.
